er commissioned the church, he believed that its economy of salvation could save him from the syphilis that afflicted his body and stained his soul. However, while implementing that economy, Cram, whose architectural theory, social commentary, and ghost stories were pessimistic about reviving the Gothic in the modern world, also created an architecture haunted by the sickness of humanity. Painstakingly researched and lavishly illustrated, Ghost Storeys redefines the allegorical relationship between a marginalized church and the Gothic Revival movement as a global interdisciplinary phenomenon.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAnglican church buildingsxOntarioxWindsor. 0aAnglican church buildingszOntariozWindsor. 0aChurch architecturexDetailsxOntarioxWindsor. 0aChurch architecturexDetails. 0aChurch architecturexOntarioxWindsor. 0aChurch architecturezOntariozWindsor. 0aGothic revival (Architecture)xOntarioxWindsor. 0aGothic revival (Architecture)zOntariozWindsor. 7aARCHITECTURE / Buildings / Religious.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077354990640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773549906423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773549906/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles